### For-Range Loop

The `range` keyword iterates over data structures.

### Range Over Slice/Array

```go
nums := []int{10, 20, 30}
for index, value := range nums {
    fmt.Printf("nums[%d] = %d\n", index, value)
}

// Skip index with _
for _, value := range nums {
    fmt.Println(value)
}

// Skip value
for index := range nums {
    fmt.Println(index)
}
```

### Range Over Map

```go
ages := map[string]int{"Alice": 30, "Bob": 25}
for key, value := range ages {
    fmt.Printf("%s is %d years old\n", key, value)
}
```

Map iteration order is NOT guaranteed.

### Range Over String

Iterates over runes, not bytes:

```go
for index, runeValue := range "Hello, 世界" {
    fmt.Printf("%d: %c\n", index, runeValue)
}
```

### Range Over Channel

```go
ch := make(chan int)
go func() {
    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        ch <- i
    }
    close(ch)
}()

for value := range ch {
    fmt.Println(value)
}
```

### Range Over String vs Bytes

| Type | Iterates Over | Value Type |
|------|---------------|------------|
| string | runes | rune |
| []byte | bytes | byte |
| []int | elements | int |
| map[K]V | key-value pairs | K, V |
| channel | received values | element type |

### Go 1.22+ Range Improvements

In Go 1.22+, `range` can iterate over functions:

```go
// Custom iterator (experimental in 1.22, stable in 1.23+)
for i := range squares(5) {
    fmt.Println(i)
}
```

> **Key Point:** Range over strings iterates over Unicode code points (runes), not bytes. The index is the byte position, not the rune index.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    // Slice
    fruits := []string{"apple", "banana", "cherry"}
    for i, fruit := range fruits {
        fmt.Printf("%d: %s\n", i, fruit)
    }

    // Map
    capitals := map[string]string{
        "US": "Washington",
        "UK": "London",
        "JP": "Tokyo",
    }
    for country, capital := range capitals {
        fmt.Printf("%s -> %s\n", country, capital)
    }
}
